<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Draft Deregulation Bill</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">John Trevelyan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on the rights of way </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">provisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> in the Draft Deregulation Bill (Clauses 12 to 18 and Schedule 6)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></h3><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:12.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most of the provisions in the Draft Bill seek to make fit for purpose provisions in the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 ('the 2000 Act') that have not been commenced. The Committee should assess the merits of implementing the 2000 Act provisions as proposed to be amended against an alternative of repealing them, not least because of their financial effect.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:12.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions are not deregulatory in that most of them increase burdens rather than reduce them.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:12.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions make rights of way legislation more complex, rather than simpler. Complexity adds cost. This falls particularly on the local authorities with rights of way management responsibilities, but has not been taken into account in the impact assessments. Other costs have been ignored in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assessments,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the claimed overall saving arises largely from one proposal: scrapping advertising in local newspapers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:12.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is inconsistency in the government's approach, both within the provisions in the Draft Bill and between those provisions and decisions on similar matters not covered by the Bill.</span></li></ul><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h3><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have been a rights of way consultant and trainer since 1999. Prior to that I worked for the Ramblers' Association for more than 20 years, leading on its rights of way work. I am submitting this evidence because I consider that the rights of way provisions in the Draft Bill, taken with the yet-to-be-commenced provisions in the 2000 Act that the Draft Bill amends, complicate, rather than simplify, the legislation and procedures, and that there is no overall financial or other benefit to justify their implementation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My experience includes the co-authorship of all four editions of a leading textbook, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Rights of way : a guide to law and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and involvement in the passage through Parliament of both the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 ('the 1981 Act'), which made substantial changes to rights of way procedures and publicity for orders, and the Rights of Way Act 1990. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a consultant, my clients have included landowners, local authorities and user groups. I was also employed by the contractors working on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Discovering Lost Ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> project. I was commissioned by the Rights of Way Law Review to write an article on the proposals of the Stakeholder Working Group set up by Natural England after it scrapped the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Discovering Lost Ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> project, proposals that form the basis of many of the provisions in the Draft Bill.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The rights of way provisions in the Draft Bill</span></h3><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions can be grouped under three headings:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Amendments to the 'cut-off' provisions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clauses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 12, 13, 14 and Schedule 6 paragraphs 5 and 8 amend the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">'cut-off' provisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Those provisions are contained in sections 53-56 of the 2000 Act and section 54A of the 1981 Act, but have not yet been commenced.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Amendments to the public path order application provisions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clauses 15 and 17 amend the provisions for applications for public path orders contained in section 118ZA, 118C, 119ZA, 119C and 121A-121E of the Highways Act 1980, none of which have yet been commenced.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Other proposals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provisions are contained in Clause 16 and Schedule 6 paragraphs 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,3,4,6,7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and 9.</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The context</span></h3><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions in the Draft Bill need, I suggest, to be considered in the context of local authority rights of way functions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Those local authorities that are categorised as both highway and surveying authorities have duties in relation to the definitive map and keeping rights of way maintained and free from obstruction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are 138 such authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not counting the Isles of Scilly or the 12 inner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> boroughs (as the latter are not required to prepare a definitive map):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">County councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">27</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Metropolitan district councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">36</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unitaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">55</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Outer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> boroughs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TOTAL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">138</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My assessment of the lengths of the rights of way networks in these authorities indicates that the 50% of authorities with the longest networks account for 97% of the total length. This means that there are many authorities with a relatively small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">network,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and limited staff resources to match. Those authorities are urban in nature, and could be particularly affected by the cut-off provisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a further 224 authorities with powers to make public path orders, and to which the provisions in the Bill relating to public path order applications, and publicity for public path orders, will also apply:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shire districts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">201</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National park authorities and Broads Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> boroughs and City of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sub-total</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">224</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Total number of authorities with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">path order-making powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">362</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In order to try to get a picture of the current state of definitive map work in surveying authorities I investigated recently the online registers of applications for definitive map modification orders in a range of authorities that include, or are close to, constituencies of Committee members. The results are in Appendix 1: they suggest to me that: (a) many authorities are not complying with their existing duties in respect of the registers; (b) many authorities already have significant backlogs of applications.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Are the provisions deregulatory?</span></h3><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have the following three examples to illustrate the points made above in the summary about the addition of burdens and the increase in complexity that surveying authorities and others will have to contend with.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first is that the cut-off provisions (as proposed to be amended by the Draft Bill) will introduce five new, additional, categories of rights of way:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant highway - s 54(2) &amp; (3) of the 2000 Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">retained highway - s 54(4)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">excepted highway - s 53(5)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">protected right of way - s 55A(2)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">designated right of way - s 56A</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The second is that there is currently a single procedure for definitive map modification orders and applications for such orders - to be found in Schedules 14 and 15 to the 1981 Act govern procedure for applications and orders. Under the Draft Bill's provisions there will be three additional variations:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">modification consent order - Schedules 14 and 15 as amended by Schedule 15A </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orders to correct administrative errors - Schedules 14 and 15 as amended by regulations (drafts of which have not been published, so their effect is uncertain)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">procedure on appeals against refusal to make orders - Schedule 15 as amended by paragraphs 3A, 3B, 3C and 3D</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The third is that if the proposals in the Draft Bill are adopted there will be four different types of Schedule 14 application:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> already made, or made before the amendments in the Bill are commenced. They are, or will be, recorded in the register and notified to landowners and occupiers. They will (in the absence of any retrospective provision in the Bill) continue to be dealt with under the existing provisions. The evidence in Appendix 1 of my researches suggests that that process will continue for many years.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made after commencement, but which have not been the subject of preliminary assessment. They will not be recorded in the register, nor will they be notified to landowners and occupiers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">after commencement and which have passed the preliminary assessment, but do not qualify to be considered for modification consent orders. They will be recorded in the register, and will be notified to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landowners and occupiers, and will therefore be dealt with under the provisions in Schedule 14 as amended by the Bill.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">after commencement and which have passed the preliminary assessment, and which do qualify to be considered for modification consent orders. They will be recorded in the register, and will be notified to landowners and occupiers, and will either be dealt with under the provisions in Schedule 14 as amended by the Bill, if no consent order is made, or under Schedule 14 as amended by Schedule 15A.</span></li></ul><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The cut-off provisions and proposed amendments</span></h3><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_0320-09_para2"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following remarks were made by Mr Michael </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Meacher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> MP, the then Minister for the Environment during the passage of the Countryside and Rights of Way Bill through Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></a></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intend to introduce proposals to encourage the completion of the record of historic rights of way within 25 years, subject to the provision of adequate resources to complete the task within that time scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">."</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(Second Reading </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hansard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, 20 March 2000, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">col</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 729</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e shall use the regulation-making power in clause 59 to require regular progress reports from local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Report, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hansard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, 14 June 2000, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">col</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 952)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I now come to the key point--resources--which was mentioned with such conviction by my hon. Friend the Member for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Denton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Reddish. We are committed to providing local authorities with the additional resources which the regulatory impact assessment estimated would arise from the proposals. Although I cannot anticipate the outcome of the current spending review, I can say that we are also examining the possibility of providing additional funding for research by non-governmental organisations into the existence of rights of way.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Report, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hansard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, 14 June 2000, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">col</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 953)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee needs to be aware that in the 13 years since passage of the Act:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">no additional resources have been made available to local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or to non-governmental organisations, and, so far as I am aware, none have been promised for the future</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the regulation-making powers (now in section 71 of the 2000 Act) have not been used, and the government indicated in its 2012 consultation document (paragraph 9.1) that it does not intend to use them to monitor progress with the cut-off provisions, despite a recommendation to do so from the Stakeholder Working Group</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the provisions are commenced in 2015 (assuming passage of an Act in 2014), then there will be little more than 10 years in which applications and the underlying research can be made before the cut-off date, a substantially shorter timescale than was envisaged in 2000 would be required if adequate resources were provided. If applications are not made to the extent envisaged by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, then there is a risk that public rights of way will be lost.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is my submission to the Committee that it should examine the amendments proposed in the Draft Bill to the cut-off provisions alongside the provisions themselves, and with an alternative approach in mind of repeal of the provisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I make that submission for the following reasons: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Implementation of the cut-off provisions will be a major project. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra's</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> estimates (in the Impact Assessment) are that there will be 20,000 additional applications, costing local authorities on average £2,900 to determine. That adds up to £58 million, with extra costs to be added for both central and local government in order-making and dealing with appeals against refused applications and with objections to orders. The total cost to the public purse could easily be £100 million. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Such a major project justifies proper management. But not only are there no plans in place: the provisions in the Bill for the Secretary of State's jurisdiction over applications for directions to be transferred to the courts (Schedule 6 paragraph 6(4)), and for applications to be recorded in the register only after the preliminary assessment (Schedule 6 paragraph 4) means that keeping track of what is happening will be much more difficult than would otherwise be the case.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the Explanatory Notes (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 64) it is acknowledged that "The investigations of applications based on evidence about the position before 1949 can be very difficult for authorities". That difficulty, which will apply also to applicants, may well lead to applicants erring on the side of caution and submitting applications for routes that would not, in practice, be extinguished at the cut-off date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The increased complexity of dealing with applications made after the cut-off date - judging whether a right of way existed in 1949 and, if so, whether it was extinguished at the cut-off date or whether an exemption from extinguishment applied - will give rise to increased, continuing, costs for both local and central government. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act 2006 extinguished rights for mechanically-propelled vehicles in certain circumstances, essentially a trial run of similar provisions. It has led to extra work considering whether exemptions apply and several court cases on its interpretation. The greater extent and complexity of the cut-off provisions in the 2000 Act suggests that the extra work involved will be significant.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The main purpose of the provisions was supposed to be greater certainty. But this must be questionable, as the lack of resources means progress will be slow. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is estimating that there will be 20,000 additional applications, which means an average of 2,000 per year. There is no evidence that authorities will be able to cope with anything like that number. If so, many thousands will remain undetermined at the cut-off date, and it will be many years before they are all resolved, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the associated uncertainty. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Moreover the proposals in the Bill on preliminary assessment of applications and associated delays in recording in the register mean that many of those will be hidden from public view by not being in the public register, nor will they have been notified to landowners, with consequent implications for property sales. Furthermore the provisions do not extinguish rights over ways that might be considered to have the greatest impact on landowners - ways not presently recorded at all, but which qualify to be recorded as either byways open to all traffic or restricted byways.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However the Act is worded that if a footpath or bridleway that existed as a public right of way in 1949 is not recorded on the definitive map at the cut-off date it will be extinguished (unless an exemption applies). This means that in any question about the status of a way after the cut-off date the starting point is that the rights were extinguished unless it can be shown that the right of way did not exist in 1949 or that an exemption applies. The difficulty of ascertaining the status in 1949 is accepted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (see above): the exemptions are in section 54 of the 2000 Act (which I, as a practitioner with many years' experience, find very difficult to understand) and possibly in regulations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has not published any draft regulations, so it is impossible to judge what effect any regulations might have.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The extinguishment of footpaths and bridleways is likely to have a particular effect in urban areas, where many such ways (mostly footpaths) are often not currently recorded on definitive maps. The Act provides no exemption for ways that are in regular daily use, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for those that are maintained by the local authority at public expense, so the only certain safeguard will be recording of the way on the definitive map. I consider that there are many thousands of such ways in regular daily use by people going to school, shops, work, etc that will be put at risk by implementation of the cut-off provisions. They range from centuries-old routes in towns and cities to ways on housing estates built in the 1930s.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">j)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local authorities that are highway authorities have a duty to keep an up-to-date list of those ways that are publicly maintainable, including footpaths and bridleways. They use that information not only to plan their maintenance work, but also, for example, to answer questions related to property transfer. At the cut-off date, there will be considerable uncertainty about the status of footpaths and bridleways included in that list: do authorities amend the list, or, if they continue to maintain ways where the rights have been extinguished, will they be spending money unlawfully?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The implementation of the cut-off provisions does not have universal support. The Equestrian Access Forum, whose members are the British Horse Society, the Byways and Bridleways Trust, the British Driving Society, the National Federation of Bridleway Associations and the South Pennine Packhorse Trails Trust, published a report in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Making Ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> for Horses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposal 2 was the repeal of the cut-off provisions.</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I therefore ask the Committee to consider the provisions as a whole, not just the amendments proposed in the Draft Bill, and to judge whether their implementation would be more in the public interest than their repeal. Although I do not object to the principle of those amendments, on which I comment below, they will add further to the complexity and costs of the cut-off provisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the Committee concludes that the cut-off provisions should be implemented I ask the Committee to consider recommending that two provisions be included as further amendments to the 2000 Act, rather than relying on the possibility that regulations may at some point be made. Both provisions would implement recommendations of the Stakeholder Working Group, and would be based on similar safeguards contained in section 67 of the Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act 2006.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first provision would protect from extinguishment any ways that were the subject of applications received before the cut-off date, regardless of whether they had been subject to the preliminary assessment test (if that is introduced). The second would protect from extinguishment any way that can be shown to have been maintainable at public expense at the cut-off date.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have the following comments on the content of the provisions in the Draft Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Clause 12 </span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In subsection (1) what is the meaning of "make a modification"? It is not a phrase used in other rights of way legislation. Does it include or exclude confirmation of a modification order made prior to the cut-off date? In subsection (1) "might affect the exercise" seems imprecise, as does "the only basis for considering that the modification is requisite".</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Subsection (2) assumes that the surveying authority has kept a copy of the definitive map and statement at the cut-off date, but imposes no duty on the surveying authority to do so. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Subsection (3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b) defines "definitive map and statement" by reference to the 1981 Act. However the definition in that Act is not entirely clear. Does it mean the original (or last revised or last consolidated) definitive map and statement on their own, or does it mean that map and statement together with all the modification and reclassification orders that have taken effect since the relevant date or date of review of the map? In some areas there will be a very significant difference.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Paragraph 67 of the Explanatory Notes suggests that this clause will "reduce the burden on local authorities that arises from having to consider in detail applications for modifications which require an investigation of historical evidence". I disagree. It will still be open to anyone to make an application, which will have to be investigated and determined by the surveying authority. Only if the authority concludes that the tests in subsection (1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a) and (b) are met will the it be able to reject the application, and it will still be possible for such a rejection to be the subject of an appeal to the Secretary of State. I therefore question whether there will be any significant saving, although I accept that if the clause succeeds in its purpose it will offer protection to public rights of way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Clause 13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the absence of draft regulations it is difficult to judge the likely success of this provision. However I consider that the task of the surveying authority will be made significantly harder by the other provisions in the Bill, notably those relating to the preliminary assessment and the associated non-recording of applications in the register. There is a suggestion in paragraph 69 of the Explanatory Notes that there may be unnecessary duplication of research effort. I suggest that this is made much more likely if individuals and the voluntary sector are unable to find out for which routes applications have been submitted, because those applications have not been recorded in the public register pending their preliminary assessment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provision appears to assume that, immediately after the cut-off date, the surveying authority will be able to identify which public rights of way were extinguished at that date. I consider this extremely unlikely, as "the investigation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of ... the position before 1949 can be very difficult for authorities" (Explanatory Notes, paragraph 64).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Clause 14</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In common with the corresponding provisions in the 2000 and 2006 Acts, this clause does not provide any procedure for ascertaining whether private rights were created at the cut-off date. The Committee may wish to enquire of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> what procedure a person with an interest in land would have to use in order to demonstrate that they had a private right of way under the Clause, how much that might cost them, and how many such cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> considers there to be?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It seems to me that there will be instances where deciding whether a private right exists will not be straightforward. Take two examples. In the first, suppose I have access from the front of my property onto a road, not affected by the cut-off provisions, and from the back onto a footpath, extinguished under the cut-off provisions. Is it "reasonably necessary" for me to continue to be able to have access along the footpath? In the second, the property is accessed by a footpath running between two roads, and lies about one-fifth of the way along the path. Is it "reasonably necessary" for the property to have a right of way along the footpath in both directions? If the answer is that it depends on the particular circumstances of the case, then I suggest that the provision does not offer that much of a guarantee to affected landowners.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Schedule 6 paragraphs 5 and 8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> (modification consent orders)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I question whether these provisions are needed. If a landowner is willing, there is nothing to prevent an unrecorded right of way from being the subject of a diversion order under the existing powers in section 119 of the Highways Act 1980. This was recognised by a specific statement in circular 1/83 issued by the Department of the Environment when the 1981 Act provisions came into force (annex A, paragraph 10) and repeated in circular 2/93 (annex B, paragraph 7). The same applies to an extinguishment order reducing the width of a way. The only other provision in proposed section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">54B(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2) that can be included in a special order is an order imposing a new limitation or condition affecting the right of way, and I suggest most of the likely requests for such conditions can be dealt with via authorisation under section 147 of the Highways Act 1980, as proposed to be amended by Clause 16 of the Draft Bill.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reference in subsection (1)(a) of proposed section 54B to section 53(3)(c)(ii) means that these provisions will apply applications to reduce the recorded status of a way, e.g. from bridleway to footpath. This is contrary to the recommendation from the Stakeholder Working Group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not clear whether the reference in subsection (1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a) to "such modifications as appear to the authority to be requisite" in 54B(1)(a) means that the authority has to be satisfied that a modification should be made. If it does, then the authority has to have undertaken a full investigation of the evidence, within the tight timetable imposed by subsection (8) (making a consent order not more than 6 months after completing the preliminary assessment).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not clear what 'documentary evidence' in subsection (1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b) means. In rights of way jargon, documentary evidence is considered to be distinct from user evidence. However in Schedule 14 to the 1981 Act (paragraph 1(b)) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">documentary evidence is defined as "including statements of witnesses". If documentary evidence in subsection (1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b) is intended to be interpreted the same way, it would appear that an applicant could prevent this section applying by submitting a single form containing evidence of use at some time after 1949.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also not clear who decides whether the documentary evidence relied on by the applicant "relates only to the existence of a right of way before 1949"? Presumably it is the surveying authority, in which case there is an additional burden on the authority. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The section appears to apply to situations in which either the surveying authority is itself the landowner or where the applicant is also the landowner. Given the restricted rights of objection (in proposed Schedule 15A), that would seem to offer the possibility of modification consent orders being made in situations which will appear less than transparent to users.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As draft guidance (subsection (6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)) or order (subsection (9) has been published, it is not impossible to judge what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has in mind for those provisions, or what the implications might be. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In subsection (3) of section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">54C(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3) the usual wording that a way will be a "highway maintainable at the public expense" has not been used (see for precedent section 49 of the 2000 Act). Instead it says that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authority are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> responsible for maintaining the way. Does this mean that the way will be a highway maintainable at public expense (and therefore potentially subject to section 56 of the Highways Act 1980 if it is out of repair, or not?)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I consider that the timetable in subsection (8) imposes serious burdens on a surveying authority. Within 6 months of serving notice following the preliminary assessment, the authority will have to:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decide whether the modifications sought by the application are requisite (which will include considering any evidence put forward by the owners and occupiers once they have been notified of the application);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decide whether the documentary evidence relied on by the applicant relates only to existence of right of way before 1949;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ascertain whether every owner agrees, or agrees with conditions</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decide whether to make a modification consent order (which ought to involve consultation with other local authorities and councils and user groups);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.22pt; padding-left:9.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the modification consent order.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the authority fails to meet this timetable, or decides not even to try, then it appears that the application will have to be dealt with in the same way as any other application. The Impact Assessment does not appear to contain any estimates for the number of consent orders that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expects to be made, although the Explanatory notes claim (paragraph 327) that the measure will reduce the burdens on central and local government.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I suggest that the number of orders likely to be made is small, and any saving will be offset by the cost of the additional complexity involved.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Applications for public path orders and proposed amendments</span></h3><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impact assessment for these provisions shows an estimated negative net present value of nearly £48m, i.e. there will be net burdens, falling particularly on landowners who may wish to make applications. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given that there has been an interval of 13 years since the original enactment of the provisions, the Committee may wish to seek evidence of the problems that landowners have faced during this time in securing diversions, and the extent to which those problems would be ameliorated by implementation of the provisions as proposed to be amended.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I suggest that an element of cost has been ignored in this assessment, in that the proposed procedure will apply only to some public path orders: others will continue to be dealt with under existing procedures, thereby causing additional confusion and complexity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Subsection (2) and (3) of Clause 15 seek to provide a power to make regulations to extend the scope of the provisions. No draft regulations have been published, so it is not possible to judge what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has in mind, and what the implications might be. There is though a general question: what if someone wants to divert a path that runs partly, but not wholly, over land covered by the provisions? Can an application be made under the provisions, or not?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the Committee's questions is whether the same result could be achieved in other ways. There is an existing provision in section 120 of the Highways Act 1980 whereby the Secretary of State is empowered to make diversion orders. The current policy is that "these powers will be exercised only exceptionally" (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> circular 1/09, paragraph 10.2). There seems to me to be no reason why the policy could not be changed to achieve a result very similar to that intended by the proposed legislation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the legislation as passed in the 2000 Act, there are provisions, for example in subsection (7) of section 118ZA, whereby, if no decision has been made on an application after four months, for an applicant to seek a direction from the Secretary of State to the council setting a date.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Such provisions mirror the existing provisions in the 1981 Act for applicants for definitive map modification orders, except that in that Act applicants are made to wait 12 months rather than four. However the Draft Bill proposes to remove the 1981 Act provisions and require applicants instead to apply to the magistrates' court. The Explanatory Notes (paragraph 342) describe the existing provision as "widely regarded as ineffective" (more comment on this below).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If those powers are so ineffective that they need to be replaced, why has no similar provision been included in the amendments to the provisions for applications for public path orders? It seems, to say the least, inconsistent. Moreover there is a marked difference between the provision for applicants for diversion orders (mainly farmers and landowners), who will be entitled to a no-charge application to the Secretary of State if their application is not determined within 4 months and that for applicants for modification orders (mainly individuals, parish councils and user groups) who will have to apply to the courts, at substantial financial risk, and then only if the application is not determined after 12 months.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I therefore conclude that these provisions add a financial burden, add complexity (and therefore cost) and are inconsistent with other provisions in the Draft Bill. I therefore ask the Committee to consider whether their implementation would be more in the public interest than their repeal.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Other provisions</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Modifications arising from administrative errors (Sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">edule</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">graph</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has published neither a draft of the regulations referred to in subsections (1) and (2) of the proposed section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">53ZA nor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a draft of the guidance referred to in subsection (4). It is therefore difficult to judge what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has in mind, and what the implications might be. The provision needs to be judged against the rather different recommendation from the Stakeholder Working Group: "</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There should be provision for basic factual corrections and clarifications of the definitive map and statement, even after the cut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">off, subject to clear guidance and appropriate safeguards.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the interpretation of the section will, if challenged, ultimately be a matter for the courts rather than guidance, and I consider that the terms "administrative error" and "obvious" are nothing like as straightforward when applied to definitive maps and statements as they might appear. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impact assessment estimates that implementation of this proposal will lead to a reduction in the number of cases going to the Secretary of State of between 10 and 20 a year, with a cost saving of between £119-238,000 annually. It seems odd that modifications arising from "obvious administrative errors" should be so contentious, and I do not recall seeing that many Inspectors' decisions on opposed modification orders dealing with such cases. The Committee may wish to ask </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to provide a list of the Inspectors' decisions made in 2011 and 2012 where the modifications arose from "obvious administrative errors" in order to substantiate the claimed numbers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I therefore question the figures for claimed financial saving, and suggest that they need to be set against the extra cost to authorities of the increased complexity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Definitive map modification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> applications and appeals (Sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">edule</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 6 para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">graph</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">s 4 and 6)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Preliminary assessment of applications</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Impact Assessment makes two assumptions in reaching a conclusion that this provision will result in an annual saving of £348,000 a year to local authorities. The first is that 10% of applications will be rejected at this stage, and that this will amount to 120 applications each year (at an average cost of determination of £2,900). The second is that the preliminary assessment will not cost authorities anything to undertake.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am not aware of any evidence to support the 10% estimate. Indeed, given that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has not published any draft of the guidance (proposed sub-paragraph 1A(2) of Schedule 14) that is intended to help authorities decide whether there is a reasonable basis for an applicant's belief that the map and statement should be modified, it would be difficult for any estimate to be prepared. Any estimate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that was prepared should allow for the probability that some applications rejected at this stage will be re-submitted with additional evidence and will then pass the test and proceed to determination, i.e. there will be no saving in such cases.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As there is no right of appeal against refusal at preliminary assessment stage, I consider that renewed applications are likely. I also consider that this provision, if implemented, is likely to be an early contender for an application to the courts for judicial review of an authority's refusal, at which point the courts will provide guidance on what constitutes a 'reasonable basis' for an applicant's belief and the work that an authority has to undertake before making its decision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I certainly dispute that the preliminary assessment will not cost authorities anything to undertake. My assessment of the provisions is that they will be obliged to undertake the following additional tasks to those included in the present requirements under Schedule 14:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Examine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">application and associated evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research any documentary evidence relied on by the applicant but for which copies have not been supplied under sub-paragraph 1(3).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Having regard to guidance issued by the Secretary of State, decide whether the application and the evidence show that there is a reasonable basis for the applicant's belief that the map and statement should be modified.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notify the applicant of the decision.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the decision is that there is a reasonable basis (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this to occur </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">90% of the time), investigate who are the owners and occupiers of all the land to which the application relates, and serve notice on them.</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the estimates in the Impact Assessment of an average cost of determining an application of £2,900 and 10% of applications failing the preliminary assessment are accepted, then it will be necessary for the average cost of a preliminary assessment to be under £290 for there to be any saving from this new provision. If the proportion of rejected applications is lower, the likelihood of any saving is reduced still further.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I consider that in some cases the work involved in items (b) and (e) in the list will cost authorities more than that sum, and generally I would question whether there will be any saving.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Moreover I can foresee difficulties arising with both applicants and owners and occupiers. Many applicants for modification orders do so as a 'one-off' because they are responding to a particular local situation - they do not have a good understanding of the procedures. If their application passes the preliminary assessment test, but is then rejected on full determination, how easy will it be for them to understand that, and will that then lead to an increase in the number of appeals? Will landowners understand that the preliminary assessment test is just that, or will they feel that the application has been decided by the authority before they have even been notified about it, let alone given the opportunity to express their views or submit evidence?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Paragraph 2 of Schedule 6 removes the 'reasonably alleged' test that applies to some applications at present. I suspect that the 'reasonable basis' test in this provision will be seen in time as reinstating something very similar.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I therefore question whether this provision will achieve any financial saving. If it does not, then I suggest the added complexity that it will bring is reason enough for it to be rejected.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By way of an alternative approach, I consider that there is scope to amend the present arrangements, which are set out in the regulations governing the keeping of registers of applications (SI 2005 No 2461). At present these require an application to be recorded in the register within 28 days of receipt, even if the applicant has not by then provided a certificate of service of notice of the application on owners and occupiers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I suggest that a reasonable alternative, which would require only amending regulations, would be to allow an authority three months from the certificate of service of notice before the application was recorded, and to provide that an application rejected in that period would not have to be recorded in the register. This would allow authorities to reject any obviously deficient application, but not require them to go through all the requirements in the proposals in the Draft Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Dealing with non-determination of an application</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently applicants for modification orders (mainly individuals, parish councils and user groups) may apply to the Secretary of State if their application has not determined after 12 months. There is no charge for such an application, and the Secretary of State has the power to set a deadline by which the surveying authority must make a decision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Explanatory Notes claim (paragraph 342) claim this provision "is widely regarded as ineffective". It is not clear what the evidential basis is for the claim. My impression is that in most cases the Secretary of State decides not to issue a direction to the surveying authority, so to that extent it would be fair to regard the exercise of the power as being ineffective in ensuring that surveying authorities determine applications in a reasonable time. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However that is a reflection on the way the power has been exercised by successive Secretaries of State since it was introduced in the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. It does not follow that the procedure itself is inherently ineffective and needs to be replaced.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The alternative proposed in the Draft Bill is to require applicants to apply to the magistrates' court. The Impact Assessment claims that this would involve applicants in a fee of £200. It is correct that the fee to commence proceedings is that sum (Schedule to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Magistrates’ Courts Fees (Amendment No. 2) Order 2010 SI 2010 No 1917</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">). However there is an additional fee of £500 if the hearing is contested, which I suggest should be assumed to be likely. Moreover the normal procedure in such cases is for the losing side to pay the costs of the winning side, so an applicant who fails to persuade the magistrates to grant an order is likely to be required to pay the costs of the surveying authority. Applicants may feel intimidated by the prospect of a court appearance, and will thus either be deterred, or will wish to have their own legal representation. The potential costs add up.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore there is specific provision in the Draft Bill for a successful application to be the subject either of an appeal to the Crown Court by the authority or an owner or occupier of land affected by the application, or of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further application by the authority to the magistrates' court to extend the period specified in the court order by up to 12 months. All these possible further court proceedings are reasons why applicants for modification orders are, in my view, likely to be deterred from considering using this procedure if introduced. It will come to be regarded as even less effective than the current procedure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also questionable how good or consistent the decision-making by magistrates will be. In my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">county</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Norfolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there is one surveying authority - Norfolk County Council - but 350 magistrates and at least three magistrates' courts in which applications might be heard. How much training, to how many, and at what cost, will be given to magistrates on these new procedures if introduced?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I therefore conclude that this proposed change will be detrimental to the recording of public rights of way and should be rejected.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A further detailed point is that the power of a court to make an order on an application made following non-determination after 12 months, contained in new paragraph 1D(5), relates to the duty imposed by new paragraph 1C. In turn that duty arises only after the notice has been served following the preliminary assessment. But what if no preliminary assessment has been undertaken - does the court have no power to make an order?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Other detailed comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="75" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6 paragraph 6(2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b) - new sub-paragraph 1(3) in Schedule 14 to the 1981 Act: what does "have access to a particular piece of documentary evidence" mean? For example, all authorities have access to documents in the National Archives, either by making a journey to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or by placing an order for a copy, so are those covered? </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6 paragraph 6(8) - new sub-paragraph 3B(5)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Schedule 14 to the 1981 Act: what does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have in mind for the Secretary of State's notice - is it intended that the only public notice will be published on the government website www.gov.uk? If so, the list of headings on that website is 'Policies', 'Publications', 'Consultations', 'Statistics', 'Announcements'. Under which of those headings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would an interested person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be expected to look? </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6 paragraph 6(11) - new paragraph 4A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Schedule 14 to the 1981 Act: two questions. First, what if the applicant has died? It is not clear that his executors have power to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a transfer. Second, why is there no provision for transfer after determination by the authority? The applicant has rights under the Inquiry Rules if an order is opposed, and an applicant might wish to arrange for someone else to take over the case at that stage.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Publicity for definitive map and public path orders (Sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">edule</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 6 para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">graph</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">s 7 and 9)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="78" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The proposal is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> remove the requirement to advertise definitive map modification orders and public path orders made under the Highways Act 1980 in a local newspaper and replace it with a requirement to put a notice somewhere on "a website maintained by the order-making authority" (i.e. not necessarily that council's main website).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I would agree that, with the growth of use of electronic media, and the decline in readership of local newspapers, it is appropriate to review current provisions that require advertising in local newspapers but not on websites.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My criticisms of the proposals in the Bill are twofold:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a lack of consistency, in that these will be the only provisions that enable a change to be made to rights of way to be advertised in this way. See Appendix 2 for a full list of provisions and current publicity requirements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The alternative proposed is very weak, in that there is no way of knowing when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an order will be publicised or where to look on a council's website.</span></p><ol start="81" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The lack of consistency is not only as illustrated in Appendix 2. In 2009 the then government gave its response to a consultation exercise relating to planning applications which had proposed scrapping the requirement to publicise some, including those that affect public rights of way, in local papers):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Government has decided not to take forward this amendment. This means that the statutory requirement to publish certain applications in newspapers remains. It is clear from the responses that some members of the public and community groups rely on the statutory notices in newspapers to learn about planning applications in their area. The Government is not convinced that good alternative arrangements can be readily rolled out.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span></p><ol start="82" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The present government has not taken a different view, and despite recently (in the Growth and Infrastructure Act 2013) amending the legislation relating to public path orders for rights of way affected by development, did not remove the requirement to advertise such orders in local newspapers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By way of illustration, within five miles of where I live in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Norwich</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, there are five authorities with powers to make public path orders - Norfolk County Council, Norwich City Council, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Broadland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and South Norfolk District Councils and the Broads Authority. Under the proposed amendments relating to public path order applications there are also likely to be an increased number of notices placed by the Secretary of State when he is dealing with an appeal under section 121E(1)(b) of the Highways Act.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present most, if not all, of those authorities would publicise an order by way of notice in the local newspaper, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Eastern Daily Press</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where public notices are grouped together and appear in the same location in the paper each day. In future the notice will appear somewhere on their websites.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I suggest that the ideal would be a single website where all notices, consultations relating to a particular area (e.g. parish or ward) and whether emanating from central or local government could be found. However I assume that to be beyond the Committee's remit.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However there is a simple opportunity to require all the notices affected by the provisions in the Draft Bill to be advertised centrally, namely by reinstating the requirement to advertise in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">London Gazette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(abolished for public path orders by the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and introducing it as an additional requirement for definitive map modification orders. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Gazette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is now available free online, and is therefore much more accessible than it was in 1981. Moreover local authorities can, if they submit notices in a suitable electronic form, advertise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mandatory notices free of charge. The financial implications of such a provision are therefore minimal.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I also suggest two further requirements if the Committee approves the principle of transferring the publicity from a local paper to a council website. The first is that each council should be required to publish and maintain on its website a statement of where order notices are publicised. The second is that the current requirement to make a paper copy of the order and plan available on request (at a reasonable charge) should be supplemented (or replaced) by a requirement to make an electronic version available alongside the publication of the notice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I would also suggest that the Acts should be amended to permit councils to use electronic means to notify other parties that they are obliged to notify of orders, which would represent a saving in copying and postage. I see no reason why other local authorities and the prescribed user organisations could not be sent their notices and copies of orders electronically: other recipients would have to agree to such receipt.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">15 September 2013</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix 1</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The on-line registers of applications for definitive map modification orders were researched in August and September 2013. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There were 113 applications listed, the oldest dating from 2001. The register fails to state which have been determined (one is known to me to have been determined several years ago), and therefore the number outstanding will be less than 113, unless there are applications not yet recorded.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Essex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">register consists of separate files of applications and summary forms (in two different formats electronically)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which have to be studied individually to gain an overall picture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My summary, having gone through that process, is that there were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">45 applications undetermined. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> those 3 had no date of application recorded. Of the remainder 12 had been outstanding for 10 years or more (the oldest dated from 1998) and 27 had been outstanding 5 years or more. The average 'age' of an undetermined application was more than 7 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Leicestershire</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The register website page states that it was last updated 30th October 2008 (as at 12th September 2013), which does not inspire confidence that it has been kept up to date. The page contains links to 38 applications, the details of which would have to be inspected individually to ascertain the details and whether it had been determined. A sample check on a few revealed none that had been determined, with application dates going back as far as 2000. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Luton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I was unable to find a register on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Luton </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council website. A reading of the Council's </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ights of Way Improvement Plan </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that its urban rights of way have not been recorded on the definitive map.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Northamptonshire</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The register contains details of 26 applications that are listed as either 'application received' or 'under investigation'.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The oldest appears to date from 2002.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Northumberland </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The register can only be accessed via a map which gave me an error message when I tried to access it (on two separate occasions some weeks apart and using two different internet browsers), so I was unable to view the register.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">North Tyneside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I was unable to find a register on the North Tyneside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council website.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Southend</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I was unable to find a register on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Southend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council website.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Warwickshire </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:1.02pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There appear to be 127 applications outstanding. The register doesn't give the date of application and I did not have time to investigate all the individual cases to determine which had been outstanding the longest.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix 2</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Powers to create, divert or extinguish public rights of way and the requirements for giving public notice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:451.4pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding:2.85pt; vertical-align:top; width:136.4pt"><p style="margin:1pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Statutory provision</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding:2.85pt; vertical-align:top; width:315pt"><p style="margin:1pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Requirements for giving public notice</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding:2.85pt; vertical-align:top; width:136.4pt"><p style="margin:1pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defence Act 1842 s 16 </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding:2.85pt; vertical-align:top; width:315pt"><p style="margin:1pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">None</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; b